Abda	A Vehdna member of the secret Stranglers cult in Dreams of Steel, described as a red rumel man: an experienced killer within that tradition. He was subordinate to Narayan Singh and may have belonged to the Changlor band, though that connection is uncertain. During events in Taglios, he served for a time as one of the bodyguards assigned to Lady, placing him among the cultists and foreign allies around her.
Adoo	A taciturn, possibly mute gateman for the Taglian Royal Library during Water Sleeps. He was not a guard and carried no weapon, reflecting the respect given to the library's sanctity in Taglios. His work was simple but visible: opening the wrought iron gate for staff and patrons of the vast institution.
Agrip	A former Annalist of the Black Company from many generations before Croaker's modern Annals. Alongside Straw, Lees, and Holm, he helped write the Book of Kette early in the Company's second century, during its service to the Paingod of Cho'n Delor. The page places him in a much older era when the force was far larger and composed entirely of black men.
Ankou	A supernatural cat-like creature in the retinue of the Imperial new Taken sorceress Mischievous Rain in Port of Shadows. Often resembling an ordinary cat in size and manner, he was distinguished by a third eye set in the center of his forehead. His presence gives the sorceress's household an uncanny familiar-like aspect without reducing him to a normal animal.
Archon of Bone	A historical employer of the Black Company somewhere in the southern continent's uncertain past. Service to this figure was associated with the Revolt of the Chiliarchs, an episode chronicled in the Book of Set by the Annalist Coral. The page frames that period as obscure but important to the Company's remembered code, with later references treating it as a severe test of honor.
Ardath Senjak	One of the four beautiful daughters of Baron Senjak, associated with the murky beginnings of the Domination era centuries before The Black Company. She and her sisters were remembered for extraordinary loveliness, and the family appears in scattered, uncertain historical accounts. Her background belongs to the old aristocratic and sorcerous world from which later northern legends emerged.
Aridatha Singh	A Gunni officer from Gondowar who became a prominent military and political figure in Taglios during Soldiers Live. Tall, strikingly handsome, and well regarded for manners as well as competence, he built an excellent reputation in the City Battalions. His abilities as negotiator, strategist, general, and ruler mark him as one of the Protectorate's most capable leaders.
Arjana Drupada	The Purohita, or highest priest of Taglios, during Water Sleeps. A Gunni priest of Rhavi-Lemna with wild white hair like an untamed haystack, he sat on the Privy Council of the Protectorate regime. Though formally a royal chaplain, he functioned as the true voice of the priesthoods in council politics.
Arkana	A young woman from the ruling family of the Voroshk world, also known by the nickname Arko. She is presented as a minor sorceress of noble background, with pale coloring and the fair-haired appearance associated with her people. Her listed family includes Shukrat and Gromovol as cousins and Ekaterina as a sister, placing her within the dynastic structure of a powerful magical culture.
Asa	A homeless man from the squalid Buskin neighborhood of Juniper in Shadows Linger. Like many poor residents of the city, he scrounged for firewood during harsh arctic winters and found shelter around the Iron Lily tavern. The page presents him as a marginal local figure drawn into the orbit of Marron Shed and the desperate life of the district.
Baku	A mysterious young girl in the service of the sorceress Mischievous Rain during Port of Shadows, also called Firefly. She appeared to be about six years old, like her twin brother Shin, yet displayed intelligence and sorcerous ability beyond her apparent age. Her small uncanny retinue also included the cat-like Ankou.
Baladitya	An elderly, severely nearsighted Gunni copyist and translator at the Taglian Royal Library. He spent much of his life among manuscripts and tomes in the vast institution, where his poor eyesight shaped the quiet routines described in Water Sleeps. His scholarly role connects him to the preservation, copying, and interpretation of written records in Taglios.
Baldo	A travel guide from the jungles of D'loc Aloc who appeared in Shadow Games. Summoned by the monks of the Temple of Travellers' Repose, he and the companion nicknamed Wheezer were engaged to help the Black Company on its journey south. Both were described as short, elderly, wizened natives of their homeland, with Croaker regarding this guide as the more ordinary of the pair.
Banh Do Trang	A Nyueng Bao merchant, trader, and smuggler who became a longtime affiliate of the Black Company. His trade ran between Taglios and the swampy delta homeland where the great river meets the ocean, moving goods that ranged from rice to crocodile skins. Because his family handled outside commerce, he was exposed to more foreign influence than most members of his people.
Benefice	One of the new Taken, a group of powerful wizards bound to the Lady through the Rite of Taking. Male but visually difficult to distinguish from most of his peers, he was known especially for mastery of the flying carpet. His skill lay in managing large carpets and linking several others into formations, a demanding magical task admired by his mistress.
Besand	A Monitor, or commander, of the Eternal Guard near the Barrowland in the Great Forest. He held authority there during the lifetime of Bomanz, appearing in the biographical narrative connected to The White Rose. Long experience with the disguised wizard made him both an acquaintance and an antagonist, marked by wary familiarity rather than trust.
Big Bucket|Cato Dahlia	A Black Company member from Opal, recognizable by his wild hair and later known as a noteworthy sergeant. He joined the mercenary brotherhood after being accused of common theft, entering alongside Sparkle, Red Rudy, and Candles. The page presents him as a hard-edged soldier whose responsibilities grew from newcomer scut work into command.
Billygoat	A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in the first chronicle during employment in the Lady's Empire. The page identifies him as a white man from the southern continent who had not previously been to the north. He was among the veterans who crossed the Sea of Torments aboard Soulcatcher's giant galley, The Dark Wings, on the way to Opal.
Black Shroud	The nickname of a mysterious sorcerer associated with Rue in the short story Chasing Midnight: The Dark Lord as a Teen. Not a public figure, he concealed a disfigured body beneath black gauze and moved through a vaporous mist that made him difficult to observe clearly. His presentation is secretive, uncanny, and menacing from the outset.
Blade	A lean, dark-skinned man from the southern continent, originating somewhere north of Taglios. Known for outspoken hatred of priestly castes and cult leaders, he was physically fit, cool-headed in battle, and highly capable with weapons. Alongside Willow Swan and Cordy Mather, he was hired by the Prahbrindrah Drah to help organize armed resistance during the early Shadowmaster conflicts.
Blind Emon	A powerful sorceress active on the northern continent before the Domination, later associated with the mysterious Master. She is surrounded by vast cardinal-colored magic cloth that can spread across surprising distances, protect her like enchanted clothing, act as strangling tendrils, and allow flight without a carpet or rheitgeistide. Her magic gives her a distinctive and unsettling presence in Shaggy Dog Bridge.
Blister	One of the new Taken, a group of powerful sorcerers bound to the Lady through the Rite of Taking. Female, though visually difficult for Croaker to distinguish from most of her identically dressed peers, she served among the Imperial champions active in The White Rose. Her strongest magical talent was necromancy, with the page also associating that art with divination.
Bo and Lana	A Juniperean couple hired by Marron Shed during Shadows Linger to serve as caregivers for his elderly mother, June. They worked after he moved her from the impoverished Buskin neighborhood to a cottage near the Enclosure, the devotional heart of the city. Their role is domestic and local, tied to the fragile respectability he tried to build around his family.
Bomanz	A wizard and antiquities digger from Oar, the largest city of Forsberg. Educated at the Black Campus, he excelled in sorcery and later settled near the Barrowland with his wife Jasmine. His public life centered on digging for Domination-era artifacts, a respectable front that placed him close to the Eternal Guard and the ancient mysteries under their watch.
Bonegnasher|Bonecrusher	One of the Ten Who Were Taken, a group of powerful sorcerers bound first to the Dominator during the Domination and later to the Lady's Empire. Enormous even among that dreaded company, he stood eight feet tall and was described as massively muscled, grotesquely strong, and crocodile-faced. His old reputation centered on brutal physical violence as much as wizardry.
Broke	A TelleKurre king who was loyal to the Dominator during the Domination. Like other officers of that era, he bore a triangular inset in the bone of his forehead to display a jewel; as a ruler, his stone was a distinctive ruby. The page presents him as part of the ancient imperial order whose relics and symbols still carried meaning centuries later.
Brother Bear Torque	A sworn member of the Black Company and one of the three Torque brothers, alongside Stubby and Paddlefoot. The page suggests the siblings came from the eastern region of the Lady's Empire, perhaps near Rust, Frost, or Thud. They are associated with Darling's circle and are characterized by rough eastern speech, rowdy habits, and close fraternal identity.
Bubba-do	A sworn brother of the Black Company, probably a Taglian recruit from the southern continent. Croaker judged him not especially bright and noted poor hearing in his left ear, a trait that shaped how others dealt with him in the Annals. He appears as a rank-and-file soldier during the Company's difficult southern campaigns.
Bullock	An important Inquisitor in Juniper, the frigid city in the far northwest of the northern continent. Originally from the Buskin, he had knowledge of a slum other officials avoided and possessed practical investigative skill. His earlier work in the Jewel Cities also gave him command of their dialect, making him useful when paired with Croaker during Shadows Linger.
Butterbutt	A sworn brother of the Black Company from Chimney, mentioned in the short story Those Who Went Before. Along with Spangler, he was intended to become one of Croaker's physician's apprentices, though both shirked much of that training. His moniker came from a large backside and remained in use even after hard travel through the western wilderness changed his build.
Buzz|Buzzard Neck	A large, very muscular sorcerer serving as bodyguard to Two Dead, a wizard colonel in the Lady's Empire during Port of Shadows. Swift, intelligent, and physically imposing, he was well liked compared with his employer. His Company nickname came from an oversized Adam's apple, shortened from the longer form used by the soldiers around him.
Candles	A Black Company member from Opal who entered the ranks in Shadow Games alongside Big Bucket, Red Rudy, and Sparkle. Unlike some recruits whose names were assigned by the Company wizards, he already had his moniker when he joined. Croaker noted that the story behind it was long, nonsensical, and not especially interesting.
Candy	A sworn brother of the Black Company from the southern continent and, for many years, one of its most senior sergeants. Croaker described him as low-key, socially skilled, and effective without showiness, a contrast to many rougher Company men. During the band's time in Aloe, he ranked near the top of the command structure beneath the Lieutenant.
Cannon Shear	A Rebel leader active during the Port of Shadows chapter also released as Smelling Danger. Reportedly a cousin of Whisper, he operated in the conflict around Aloe while the Black Company was garrisoned there. His role places him among the opposition figures connected to Rebel military action against the Company in that region.
Cao Khi	A Nyueng Bao necromancer mentioned briefly in She Is the Darkness. He was the father of Hong Tray, the last true priestess of her people, and an ancestor within a family line important to Nyueng Bao memory. His practice was discussed rarely and with mild embarrassment, suggesting that necromancy was frowned upon in that culture.
Captain|Old Man	The leader of the Black Company during Croaker's first two chronicles, known by no personal name. Born in one of the Jewel Cities, he had been a professional soldier before joining the mercenary brotherhood and eventually rising to command. A master strategist, brusque with his own men yet unflappable around dangerous sorcerers, he relied on strong subordinates such as the Lieutenant, Elmo, Candy, and Mercy.
Carp	A sworn brother of the Black Company from the southern continent and one of its sergeants in the first chronicle. He served among the veteran noncommissioned leaders under the Captain, alongside figures such as Candy and Match. His role is practical and military rather than biographical, with no extended personal history recorded.
Case|Philodendron Case	A soldier of the Eternal Guard from a northern farming family and the main narrator of The Silver Spike. He disliked farm life, his given name, and the parents who burdened him with it, eventually leaving home in search of military adventure. His service brought him to the Barrowland, where the Guard watched over the lethal graveyard containing the Dominator and his demons.
Castle creatures	Strange, reclusive humanoid denizens of the black castle of Juniper in Shadows Linger. Their faces were described in sharp angles and shadows, with lustrous olive coldness and softly luminous eyes, and they wore black hooded clothing. Their exact nature is not fully explained, though the details suggest summoned beings or demons tied to the castle's supernatural presence.
Chandra Chan Tal	One of the most influential chief priests of the majority Gunni faith in Taglios during the Books of the South. Bald and dressed in scarlet robes, he stood among the city's powerful religious figures and was regarded by Smoke as one of its most important men. His position placed him amid rival priestly factions, including other Gunni leaders and counterparts from the Shadar and Vehdna faiths.
Chandra Gokhale	A high-ranking Gunni bureaucrat of Taglios during Water Sleeps, holding the office of Inspector-General of the Records. As a member of the Privy Council, he belonged to the administrative elite of the Protectorate. Ancient, hairless, lean, and severe, he had expanded a once-minor civic role into authority over finances and public works.
Chasing Midnight	A young auburn-haired bandit woman and inexperienced witch who plays a central role in Bone Eaters and Chasing Midnight: The Dark Lord as a Teen. Her family includes a twin brother, an older brother, and several male cousins connected to the same bandit clan west of Rue. She is also presented as a medic trainee, learning practical healing work alongside her minor sorcery.
Chasing Moonlight	A teenage bandit and inexperienced low-magnitude wizard appearing in Bone Eaters and Chasing Midnight: The Dark Lord as a Teen. Auburn-haired and twelve minutes younger than his twin sister, he belonged to a clan west of Rue with an older brother and several male cousins. Hard weather, pests, poor crops, and relentless tax collectors helped push the family into amateur banditry.
Chal Ghanda Ghan	A Taglian ambassador mentioned in Bleak Seasons alongside Ranjalpirindi. He represented the Prahbrindrah Drah during political dealings connected to Dejagore, placing him among the Prince's diplomatic agents. His role is courtly and political rather than military, tied to Taglios's attempts to influence events around the Black Company.
Chiba Vinh Nwynn	A female sergeant of the Black Company during its stationing in Aloe, counted among only nine women in the brotherhood at that time. Physically more formidable than many male soldiers, she had a difficult relationship with Croaker, who called her his near nemesis. Her duties included disciplined supervision inside the Company's compound, where her record-keeping and vigilance mattered.
Chick	A teenage bandit and loyal cousin of Chasing Midnight and Chasing Moonlight in the On The Long Run story arc. Among the cousins, he is the one most often seen directly at Midnight's side. His clan came from west of Rue and was pushed into amateur banditry by bad weather, pests, poor crops, and relentless tax collectors.
Chu	A Children of the Dead soldier from Hsien who appears in Soldiers Live as a senior military figure associated with the Black Company. He was a respected veteran in his native world before joining the outsider mercenaries, likely after service to one of Hsien's many warlords. His roles included brigade command and later general staff work, reflecting disciplined professional experience.
Clete	A native of Oar and sibling of Tokar, Glory, and the young Snoopy. Like his older brother and sister, he belonged to the Resurrectionists, the faction secretly devoted to freeing the Dominator from the Barrowland. He appears in the flashback biographical narrative surrounding Bomanz in The White Rose, where his family ties place him within the movement's local network.
Cletus	A native of the Jewel City of Beryl and brother of Loftus and Longinus. After service in the Urban Cohorts, he joined the Black Company in Shadow Games and quickly became valuable for technical expertise. The three siblings established themselves as indispensable engineers, artillery specialists, and architects within the mercenary brotherhood.
Coral	A historical Annalist of the Black Company from an unspecified number of generations before Croaker. He was remembered for writing the Book of Set, one of the volumes of the Annals. That work primarily concerned the Company's service to the Archon of Bone during the Revolt of the Chiliarchs, a dark and morally difficult period in its remembered history.
Corder	Captain of a secret Rebel cell in Tanner during The White Rose and one of Darling's informants. Known for contacts throughout the city, he served as eyes and ears for the New White Rose Rebellion against the Lady's Empire. Croaker knew his name by reputation before meeting him, recognizing the value of his long-running intelligence work.
Cordy Mather|Cordwood Mather	A wanderer from Roses who crossed paths with the Black Company in Shadow Games. Calm, patient, and steady, he was close friends with Willow Swan and Blade after years of travel through the southern continent. The three were hired by the Prahbrindrah Drah to help organize Taglios's first armed resistance against the early Shadowmaster invasions.
Corey	A young new recruit of the Black Company in Aloe during the short stories later collected in Port of Shadows. He appears around off-duty life in the city, including games of tonk with older veterans at the Dark Horse tavern. His role is that of a junior brother learning the rhythms and obligations of the mercenary band.
Cornello Crat	A sworn brother of the Black Company present in Aloe during Port of Shadows. Literate in Aloen, he was useful for work involving local written records and public documents. His role reflects how practical language skills could make an otherwise minor soldier valuable during a stationing in unfamiliar territory.
Cornie	An elderly stable keeper in the major city of Oar and a local Rebel during The Black Company. His stable served as lodging for the Company's regular supply patrols from Deal, making him a small but useful figure in the city's wartime networks. As a civilian tradesman, his politics tied him to the local opposition.
Count	A physically massive thug in Krage's gang during Shadows Linger, working in the Buskin, Juniper's poorest slum. He served as the gangster's most intimidating enforcer, though Marron Shed regarded him as less pointlessly cruel than some of the others. His big brown cow eyes and sheer size made him memorable among the local underworld figures.
Crake	A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in Shadows Linger during service to the Lady's Empire in Juniper. He was selected for the advance team flown into the city ahead of the main body, a trusted group led by Elmo and including Croaker, Goblin, Pawnbroker, Kingpin, Otto, and other veterans. His role marks him as a reliable soldier used for sensitive assignments.
Creeper	One of the new Taken, a group of powerful wizards bound to the Lady through the Rite of Taking. Unlike several peers, this individual's sex was not specified by Croaker, who could not distinguish the identically dressed sorcerers from one another except for Whisper. The name belongs to the Imperial cadre active in The White Rose.
Crispin	A sworn brother of the Black Company active during employment in the Lady's Empire. Before that northern service, he had been with the band in Beryl and crossed the Sea of Torments aboard Soulcatcher's giant galley, The Dark Wings, to Opal. His recorded role is that of a rank-and-file veteran present during the first chronicle's early imperial campaigns.
Croaker	A central Black Company figure across the Books of the North, South, and Glittering Stone. Established early as the mercenary brotherhood's physician and respected Annalist, he is also the narrator of many chronicles and short stories. Born near trade routes south of Padora, he was tall, scarred, skeptical of religion, naturally curious, and gifted at acquiring languages.
Curly	A sworn brother of the Black Company active before the first book and during the band's contract with the Syndic of Beryl. His ironic name came from being bald. Croaker's medical attention to him, including recurring treatment for crabs, gives the character a coarse barracks-life texture typical of the Company's rank and file.
Dagoth	A sworn brother of the Black Company from Chimney, recruited among the city's young lowlifes during the On The Long Run arc. He appears in Leta of the Thousand Sorrows and is associated with other new recruits from the same city. His recorded duty is modest but practical: serving as a messenger alongside the archer Zeb.
Dahrhanahdahr	A doctor from Taglios and personal physician to the Radisha Drah. She came from a family of physicians and was highly regarded for her skill, with the Princess dryly noting that even male colleagues admitted she was marginally competent. Almost certainly Gunni, she is described as tiny and wearing a pink sari during her brief appearance in Dreams of Steel.
Dancing	A notorious general from Beryl at some point in the city's long history. His infamy rested on having nearly destroyed the city, and the people still shuddered to speak his name in later times. Croaker used that reputation as the basis for a joking exclamation during The Black Company.
Darling	A blonde, deaf-mute girl from Forsberg who becomes closely connected to Raven and the Black Company in the early chronicles. She communicates through finger speech, a skill shared with Silent and gradually understood by Croaker. Her presence around the mercenary brotherhood is quiet but emotionally important, especially because others take on protective roles toward her.
Daughter of Night|Booboo	A female cult figurehead of the Stranglers, revered as the Foretold in connection with the goddess Kina. Raised under the guardianship of Narayan Singh and later linked to the Khadidas, she was dedicated from childhood to transcribing the Books of the Dead. Her role is religious, magical, and deeply bound to the cult's hopes for the Year of the Skulls.
Del Mukharjee	A worker in the Palace of Taglios during Water Sleeps, subordinate to the corrupt subassistant housekeeper Jaul Barundandi. His role involved collecting kickbacks from poverty-stricken daily laborers inside the Palace. The character reflects the petty graft and exploitation present within the Protectorate's household bureaucracy.
Dinh Luc Doc	A Nyueng Bao swordsmith who crafted the excellent blade Ash Wand about four centuries before Bleak Seasons. His hallmark near the hilt identified the weapon as his work, a detail recognized by Croaker when Uncle Doj displayed the sword in the Palace of Taglios. The brief reference places him among the respected ancient craftsmen of Nyueng Bao martial culture.
Dominator	The great evil of the northern continent and ruler of the infamous empire known as the Domination. A wizard tyrant of immense magnitude, he controlled territory through sorcery, fear, armies, and the enslaved generals called the Ten Who Were Taken. His wife, the Lady, was also central to the old imperial order, though her strategic role was historically obscured.
Doughbelly	A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned during early employment in the Lady's Empire. He had previously been with the band in Beryl and crossed the Sea of Torments aboard Soulcatcher's giant galley, The Dark Wings, to Opal. His role is that of a veteran rank-and-file soldier present during the first chronicle's northern campaigns.
Dragon	A great winged guardian of the Barrowland in the Great Forest, watching that dangerous place for more than 370 years. At least fifty feet tall, with green eyes described as ancient, wise, merciless, arrogant, mocking, and contemptuous, it was the only individual of its kind mentioned in the Annals. Its agelessness and extreme loyalty suggest a demonic rather than natural origin.
Dragonfly demon	A type of giant demon bound to the Lady, appearing briefly in The Black Company. The entities' size, speed, and power indicated that they were available only to conjurers of the highest magnitudes. Croaker's Annals describe one such monster as luminescent, emphasizing its supernatural and dangerous presence.
Edmous Black	A sworn brother of the Black Company from Aloe who served as Croaker's apprentice physician during Port of Shadows. He learned quickly and was especially valued for veterinary experience, a skill useful amid the livestock gathered during the stay in his hometown. When the band prepared to move on, he chose to remain there rather than continue with them.
Elmo	A universally respected veteran sergeant of the Black Company during the Books of the North. Croaker described him as sharp despite the appearance of a big, dumb country soldier, and regarded him as both spokesman for the enlisted men and closest friend. Earlier hints suggest a background involving farming, mines, and long service before the first chronicle begins.
Endibo	A Nar warrior from Gea-Xle and one of the thirty-three members of that elite caste who joined the Black Company in Shadow Games. His background places him among the disciplined black warriors whose martial culture made a strong impression on the mercenary brotherhood. He represents the influx of Nar soldiers from the southern city.
Exile	A powerful Imperial sorcerer who represented the empire's leadership in the beleaguered city of Oar during The Silver Spike. He was noted for honesty, fair play, and coolheaded conduct, unusual traits in the political and magical struggles around him. His wealthy, ostentatiously colored clothing led observers to compare him to a popinjay, clown, or peacock.
Faceless Man|Nameless	One of the original Ten Who Were Taken, the powerful sorcerers who served the Dominator during the Domination and later the Lady's Empire. Specific details about him are scarce because Croaker did not encounter him personally. His sigil was a simple circle, perhaps representing a zero, and his known military reputation included command activity far from the Company's immediate viewpoint.
Fade	A teenage bandit and loyal cousin of Chasing Midnight and Chasing Moonlight in the On The Long Run story arc. Among the cousins, he is the most dangerous, noted for proficiency with a crossbow and greater independence than Chick. His clan came from west of Rue and was driven into amateur banditry by hardship, poor crops, pests, and relentless tax collectors.
Fall Woo	A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in Bone Eaters, part of the On The Long Run arc. He helped lead a haggard-looking scout group at the head of its refugee train in the western wilderness. His role places him among the forward soldiers responsible for contact, screening, and first response during difficult travel.
Father Tree|Old Father Tree	An immensely powerful demon entity located at the geographic center of the Plain of Fear. Appearing as a deciduous tree with a massive trunk, he is worshipped as a god by the region's sparse human tribes and commands its strange creatures, including menhirs, windwhales, mantas, reversed centaurs, walking trees, and other beings. Change storms on the Plain are speculated to be his dreams.
Father Tree's prisoner	An unnamed sorcerer of immense magnitude, comparable to the Dominator, who subjugated a northern region in ages before the Domination. Already legendary in the Lady's youth, he was defeated by forces described as the side of light and buried alive beneath what became the Plain of Fear. Father Tree was summoned as a godlike sapling from another plane to hold him underground with its roots.
Feather	A young but powerful Rebel sorceress who was recently promoted into the Circle of Eighteen during The Black Company. Newly married to Journey, she later became one of the new Taken, whose members dressed identically except for Whisper. Her role bridges Rebel leadership and the Lady's sorcerous command structure.
Feet	A sworn brother of the Black Company from the southern continent, mentioned in Bleak Seasons. He served during the defense of Dejagore and held messenger duty at the city's walls. His brief appearance presents him as a practical rank-and-file soldier used for urgent communication during a dangerous military posting.
Fire-eater|Firedrake|Obsidian serpent	A demon also known in dormant form as an obsidian serpent. It is described with vast dark wings, red eyes like forge windows, glossy talons like obsidian knives, and a mouth filled with sharp dark teeth. The creature's fiery, winged form and artifact-like resting state mark it as one of the more visually striking supernatural entities in The Silver Spike.
First Father	The leader of the ruling family of the Voroshk world in Soldiers Live. A prince and elder patriarch, he was brother to Nashun the Researcher and father to Shukrat, placing him near the center of Voroshk dynastic authority. Like others of that family, he wore priceless shefsepoken robes and traveled by personal rheitgeistide.
First One|Master of Time	A historical Shadowmaster in the Land of Unknown Shadows, remembered chiefly through titles rather than a personal name. He is credited with creating many of the stranger Unknown Shadows inhabiting Hsien by reshaping feral shadows from the glittering plain. His work gave those beings greater intelligence and physical traits drawn from natural creatures.
Flick	An elderly man from Forsberg and grandfather of Darling in The Black Company. After entering the orbit of Raven and the mercenary brotherhood, he traveled as a camp follower and felt indebted to those who had helped him and his granddaughter. He shared Rebel stories and prophecies with Pickles, despite the Company's service to the Lady's Empire.
Freak|Heart-of-the-Lion|Heart	A tall K'Hlata warrior from the savannah south of D'loc Aloc who joined the Black Company alongside his brother Geek in Shadow Games. Armed with javelins, a long-bladed spear, and a black-and-white hide shield, he came from a striking martial culture that impressed Croaker physically. Goblin supplied the nickname, though the birth name was Heart-of-the-Lion.
Frogface	An imp from the demon worlds, standing only two feet tall but proportioned like an adult. A powerful supernatural trickster, he could disappear and reappear instantly, cleanse poison from human blood, and understand or interpret seemingly any language. He disliked being called a demon, insisted on the more precise term imp, and was old enough that Smoke speculated he might be ten thousand years of age.
Geek|Claw-of-the-Lion|Claw	A tall K'Hlata warrior from the savannah south of D'loc Aloc who joined the Black Company alongside his brother Freak in Shadow Games. Armed with javelins, a long-bladed spear, and a black-and-white hide shield, he moved with the same rhythmic precision as his sibling. Goblin supplied the nickname, though the birth name was Claw-of-the-Lion.
Ghojarindi Ghoj	The High Priest of the Shadar religion in Taglios when the Black Company first arrived in Shadow Games. He competed with the Prahbrindrah Drah and the high priests of other major faiths for influence in the city. His personal patron was Hada, goddess of Death, Destruction, and Corruption, and he commanded the subcult known as the Children of Hada.
Gilbert	An old, one-eyed, corrupt moneylender operating in the Buskin, Juniper's poorest district, during Shadows Linger. He dealt with Marron Shed, owner of the Iron Lily, and moved within the same grim local economy as gangsters, debtors, and desperate residents. His role is that of a predatory financier in the slum's underworld.
Glory	A woman from Oar, sister to Tokar, Clete, and the young Snoopy. Like her grown brothers, she belonged to the Resurrectionists, the faction secretly dedicated to freeing the Dominator from the Barrowland. Engaged to Stancil, she appears in the flashback biographical narrative surrounding Bomanz in The White Rose.
Goblin	One of the Black Company's wizards during the modern Annals, an elderly, short, skinny man with a high-pitched voice and a grin often compared to a frog or toad. His magic favored illusions and sleeping spells, making him valuable for reconnaissance and infiltration. His long-running feud with One-Eye was notorious, elaborate, and ultimately an expression of friendship.
Gossamer	An influential sorceress in the Lady's Empire during The Silver Spike and twin sister of Spidersilk. She trained in magic at the Tower at Charm and dressed in black clothing in imitation of the Ten Who Were Taken. Her profile reflects the ambition and style of Imperial wizards operating below the legendary magnitude of the Taken themselves.
Gromovol|Gromo	A young nobleman and wizard from the ruling family of the Voroshk world in Soldiers Live. He was brother to Sedvod, son of Nashun the Researcher, and nephew of the First Father, with cousins including Arkana, Shukrat, and Magadan. Raised amid immense privilege, he belonged to a magical culture defined by shefsepoken robes, rheitgeistiden, and rigid status.
Guardian	One of the mysterious creatures appointed to watch over the sacred Catacombs of Juniper. The Annals describe the Guardians only vaguely as monsters, and they seem to remain within the subterranean chambers rather than roaming the city. Their role connects them to the Custodians, who maintained the Catacombs and deposited the newly deceased there.
Gupta brothers|Sin	Two sworn members of the underground Black Company mentioned in Water Sleeps, one of whom carried the nickname Sin. They were from the southern continent and almost certainly veterans of the Kiaulune wars, though their exact race or city of origin is not specified. Like others in Taglios, they balanced ordinary work with Company affairs handled in off-hours.
Gurdlief Speak|Gurd	A chatty ten-year-old orphan boy from Aloe in Port of Shadows. Creative and fond of storytelling, he impressed Croaker by enlivening folktales with sympathetic embellishments. Though destined for the celibate priesthood of the Occupoa cult, he found that future unappealing and instead gravitated toward gossip, companionship, and local curiosity.
Guust Nolet	A female member of the Black Company in Port of Shadows and sister to Hika Nolet. The sisters were among the very small number of women in the mercenary brotherhood and dressed in men's clothing. They were evidently disliked by many others, giving them a sharp and difficult reputation within the ranks.
Hagop	One of the longest-serving members of the Black Company, usually found alongside Otto. Born in Rebosa on the southern continent, he had a polytheistic upbringing and became known as a superb scout and expert shot with a sniper's crossbow. Quiet, unsentimental, and hard to kill, he was one of the iconic veterans whose endurance symbolized the Company's survival.
Hanged Man|Crooked Neck	One of the Ten Who Were Taken, a powerful sorcerer and general in the Lady's war against the Rebel Circle of Eighteen. Improbably tall and lean, he bore the swollen, purpled neck and bent head suggested by his name, with a face frozen in a strangled rictus. He could communicate in TelleKurre and was especially associated with countering airborne pastel sorcery.
Harden	A male sorcerer and one of the most powerful members of the Circle of Eighteen in The Black Company. A major Rebel general, he was connected by family to Whisper and Raker, and was known for a vile, volatile, unpredictable temper. Croaker described his projected likeness as a giant bearded face with tangled orange hair and one eye half closed by a livid scar.
Hargadon	One of the most influential figures in Juniper during Shadows Linger. As senior Custodian, he was responsible for the Catacombs, the city's most sacred place, where the dead had been interred for centuries. Familiar with Duke Zimerlan and the city's highest circles, he embodied Juniper's religious authority and its anxiety over the black castle.
Haru	A teenage bandit and loyal cousin of Chasing Midnight and Chasing Moonlight in the On The Long Run story arc. Brother to Yuko and less often at Midnight's side than Chick or Fade, he belonged to the same clan west of Rue. Had the teenagers not been separated from their homeland by ill fortune, he would have become her husband.
Hika Nolet	A red-haired female member of the Black Company in Port of Shadows and sister to Guust Nolet. The sisters were among the very small number of women in the mercenary brotherhood and dressed in men's clothing. They were evidently disliked by many others, giving them a sharp and difficult reputation within the ranks.
Holm	A former Annalist of the Black Company from many generations before Croaker's modern writings. Alongside Straw, Lees, and Agrip, he helped write the Book of Kette early in the Company's second century, during service to the Paingod of Cho'n Delor. His era belonged to a much larger Company composed entirely of black men.
Holts	A horse doctor among the Eternal Guard during The White Rose. He was the closest thing to a physician in the Barrowland before the great conflict there, giving him a practical medical role among soldiers rather than formal status as a doctor. His presence shows the Guard's rough, provincial approach to care and diagnosis.
Hong Tray|Ky Hong Tray	An influential Nyueng Bao De Duang leader and their last true priestess. Elderly and physically frail, she retained a sharp intelligence that Murgen immediately recognized. Wife of Ky Dam, mother of Ky Gota, and grandmother of Ky Sahra, she stood at the center of a family whose ties shaped relations between the Nyueng Bao and the Black Company.
Howler	One of the Ten Who Were Taken, an ancient wizard of great knowledge and power. He appeared as a tiny, masked man wrapped tightly in dirty indigo rags, notorious for random, chilling, uncontrollable screams. Best known for creating magical artifacts, especially flying carpets, he was an unrivaled pilot and often floated in the air even when not using one.
Hungry Ghosts	Supernatural entities that haunted the Village of Hungry Ghosts west of Rue in Bone Eaters. They emitted a siren call that lured victims into an irrational trance, making the ruins taboo and widely avoided. Croaker was uncertain of their origin, but suspected old wizardry or a dawn-time god; they could exist as discorporate spirits or as incarnate possessors of living bodies.
Husky	A corporal in the Eternal Guard during the lifetime of Bomanz, appearing in the flashback biographical narrative in The White Rose. He answered to Monitor Besand and was familiar with Bomanz as a local antiquities digger. His role places him among the ordinary Guardsmen stationed near the Barrowland and its dangerous traditions.
Iluk	A jamadar in the Stranglers cult, leading the Ineld band of Vehdna extraction from Hatchpur State. Narayan Singh described his longstanding feud with Kowran, a rival jamadar of the Twana band from the same region but of Shadar background. The dispute involved accusations of heresy and poaching, and Lady interpreted it as resembling a criminal territorial conflict.
Iman ul Habn Adr	An influential priest of the Vehdna religious, racial, and cultural group in Taglios during Dreams of Steel. He stood among the city's leading cult authorities at a time when the major priesthoods competed for power and resources. His position made him one of the prominent domestic opponents of Lady's efforts to assert military authority in the city.
Isi	One of the thirty-three Nar who joined the Black Company in Shadow Games. Though his Company rank is not specified, he became a general in the Taglian army under the Prahbrindrah Drah, answering directly to Lady as the Company's Lieutenant. His role places him among the Nar soldiers who rose into command during the Shadowmaster wars.
